	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Senecaville&#44; Guernsey Co. Ohio</placeName>.</p>
				<p rend="align(right)"><date>April 27&#44; 1864</date>.</p>
				<p><addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Much please was<lb/> I a few days since to receive the <date>April</date><lb/> No. of the Occident.  so the Occident intends<lb/> to live another year&#58; it is not one of the<lb/> many things that cannot continue to live in<lb/> these times.  The Occident has been coming<lb/> to the wrong Post&#45;Office for some time.  Please<lb/> change it from <placeName>Cumberland</placeName> to <placeName>Seneca&#61;<lb/>ville&#44; Guernsey Co. Ohio</placeName>.  I send you the pay<lb/> for the present year.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I thought a year since that I would<lb/> write some articles for you&#44; but I have had<lb/> so many things on hand that it has been<lb/> neglected.  I am so constituted that I cannot<lb/> do many things at the same time and do all<lb/> well&#58; perhaps I ought to have written a doubt<lb/> whether I do any one thing very well.  I hope<lb/> to prepare some articles this summer which you<lb/> will adjudge appropriate for your magazine.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I wrote an article some time since for<lb/> the <sic>Danvill</sic> Review&#44; a Presbyterian Review<lb/> conducted by ministers and D. D. s in <placeName>Ken&#61;<lb/>tucky</placeName>&#44; having for its title&#44;&#8212;&#8220;Experiment<lb/> in Translation of the Talmud.&#8212;Valuable<lb/> Things in the Talmud.&#8221;  My article will&#44;<lb/> I suppose&#44; appear in the <date>June</date> No. The<lb/> Editors have intimated this to me.  They express</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>themselves greatly interested in &#8220;the curious and<lb/> useful contents&#8221; I <sic>criticise</sic> some historical<lb/> statements&#44; especially chronological items&#44; pro&#61;<lb/>nouncing them manifestly and mysteriously<lb/> untrue.  I mean historical statements in the<lb/> Talmud.  I suspect you would not assent<lb/> to some of my criticisms&#58; the testimony of<lb/> history on these points&#44; however&#44; cannot be<lb/> mistaken.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">It gives me great pleasure to render<lb/> any help in my power to make the Occident<lb/> an able periodical&#44; well worthy of the patronage<lb/> of the intelligent and religious community.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Yours very truly</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)"><persName role="author">M. R. Miller</persName>.</p>
		</body>
